{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/interactive-graphs-in-python-830b1e6c197f", "time": 1683010830.410711, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/interactive-graphs-in-python-830b1e6c197f/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Interactive Graphs in Python. An incredibly quick and easy extension\u2026 | by Gojo Satoru | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Interactive Graphs in Python", "description": "Python is my favorite programming language, superseding lower-level languages including Java and C++ as well as higher-level ones such as Matlab and R. One of the main reasons, besides a vast number\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [], "all_paragraphs": ["Python is my favorite programming language, superseding lower-level languages including Java and C++ as well as higher-level ones such as Matlab and R. One of the main reasons, besides a vast number of libraries and their ease of implementation, is its data visualization. Plotting things is incredibly intuitive and easy using Matplotlib and related libraries. In this article, I want to introduce ipywidgets, a library that adds an interactive slider to your graphs with realtime updates (as seen in the title image above). You are going to need to install the following libraries to follow along with this article:", "First, let\u2019s create a graph that we want to make interactive. I am going to plot a sinewave and add a slider allowing us to alter the input to the function. To create the chart I\u2019ll go ahead and use the linspace function to generate points around the unit circle creating both x-values (inputs) and y-values (outputs).", "Now that we\u2019ve effectively created our set of points we can use Matplotlib to plot them.", "Showing the figure (using plt.show()) will yield the following graph\u2026", "That\u2019s a pretty nice sinewave! But as the title of this article suggests we want to make this interactive\u2026", "You\u2019ll notice some slight changes to our original code. We included @interact from the ipywidgets library, and return the figure we created in our sinewave function. Also, we included a new parameter, c, with the default value of 1. This is the value that will be given a slider and allow the user to interact with the graph. In this case, we multiply the inputs to the sinwave function by c, allowing the user to determine the frequency of the sinewave being graphed\u2026", "It\u2019s that simple to create interactive graphs in Python! You can even vary more than one parameter by including more arguments in the graph\u2019s function, a slider will be created for each one! This really comes in handy when trying to visualize multivariate equations in a 2-dimensional space.", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes."], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F830b1e6c197f&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Finteractive-graphs-in-python-830b1e6c197f&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Finteractive-graphs-in-python-830b1e6c197f&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign In"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": ""}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fnew-story&source=---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------new_post_sidenav-----------", "anchor_text": "Write"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/search?source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------",